Add **two minimal asserts**.

## 1. End of `State.add`: modification index must refer to the previous buffer

Add this after the existing `buffer_length_previous <= buffer_length` assert, or replace the current modification-index assert block with the expanded version.

Location: after [`State.add` switch](file:///<redacted>/lex/src/lex.zig#L1134-L1138).

Recommended:

```zig
// The buffer_modification_index must point to a span that existed before this action.
assert(self.buffer_modification_index == null or
    self.buffer_modification_index.? < self.buffer_length_previous);
```

Keep the existing assert too:

```zig
assert(self.buffer_modification_index == null or
    (self.buffer_modification_index.? < self.buffer_effective.len and
    self.buffer_modification_index.? < self.buffer_length));
```

Reason: synthetic backspaces are calculated against the **previous** buffer. If a branch accidentally sets `buffer_modification_index` to an appended span, `calculate_synthetic_backspaces()` becomes wrong. This assert catches that at the producer site.

## 2. Inside `calculate_synthetic_backspaces`: previous length must still be valid

Add this before the existing `buffer_modification_index` assert.

Location: start of [`calculate_synthetic_backspaces`](file:///<redacted>/lex/src/lex.zig#L1403-L1405).

Recommended:

```zig
assert(self.buffer_length_previous <= self.buffer_length);
```

So the function becomes:

```zig
fn calculate_synthetic_backspaces(self: *State) u8 {
    assert(self.buffer_length_previous <= self.buffer_length);
    assert(self.buffer_modification_index == null or
        (self.buffer_modification_index.? < self.buffer_length_previous));

    if (self.buffer_modification_index) |buffer_modification_index| {
        return self.buffer_length_previous - buffer_modification_index;
    } else {
        return 0;
    }
}
```

Reason: `State.add` is append-only or length-preserving, so `buffer_length_previous <= buffer_length` must hold after an add. After some `backspace` paths, this can become false, so this assert documents that `calculate_synthetic_backspaces()` is for post-add replacement calculation, not arbitrary state inspection.

## Do not add more yet

I would not add a new `last_action` flag just to prove “this was called immediately after add.” That would enforce the contract more completely, but it is not minimal. The two asserts above enforce the invariants that actually protect the arithmetic:

1. `buffer_modification_index` points into the old buffer.
2. old buffer length is not larger than current buffer length when calculating.
